\begin{abstract}
Link prediction is a fundamental task in graph representation learning, where the goal is to predict missing links between nodes. Most existing approaches rely on node embeddings learned by graph neural networks and use simple decoders for link prediction, often overlooking structural information such as the shortest-path distance between nodes. In this work, we propose a distance-augmented link prediction framework that incorporates shortest-path distance into the decoding process. We encode distances using sinusoidal embeddings and use them to condition the decoder through adaptive layer normalization, allowing the model to adjust node representations based on structural proximity. Our experiments on the various datasets demonstrate that incorporating distance information leads to improved link prediction performance.
\end{abstract}
\vspace{0.5em}
\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Link Prediction, Graph Neural Networks (GNN), GraphSAGE, Distance Encoding, Adaptive Layer Normalization (AdaLN), Graph Representation Learning, Shortest-Path Distance, Sinusoidal Embedding.
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}
Link prediction is a fundamental problem in graph learning with applications in social networks, citation networks, recommendation systems, and biological networks. The task involves predicting if an edge exists between two nodes based on the observed structure of the graph and node features. With the success of graph neural networks (GNNs), link prediction is approached using an encoder–decoder framework, where the encoder generates node embeddings and the decoder estimates the likelihood of a link between node pairs.
\vspace{0.5em}

While significant effort has been devoted to designing more expressive encoders, the decoder in many existing approaches remains relatively simple, often relying on dot products or shallow multilayer perceptrons. As a result, these methods primarily depend on node embeddings and may fail to fully utilize important structural signals present in the graph.
\vspace{0.5em}

One such signal is the shortest-path distance between nodes. Nodes that are closer in the graph are usually more likely to be connected than those that are far apart. However, this information is not incorporated in most standard LP models, as message passing in GNNs primarily captures local neighborhood information.
\vspace{0.5em}

In this paper, we propose a distance-augmented link prediction framework that  incorporates shortest-path distance into the decoding process. We first compute node embeddings using a GraphSAGE encoder. We then encode the shortest-path distance between node pairs using sinusoidal frequency embeddings, which provide a smooth and expressive representation of distance. These embeddings are used to condition a decoder through adaptive layer normalization, enabling the model to modulate node representations based on structural distance before predicting links.
\vspace{0.5em}
Our approach highlights the importance of combining node embeddings with global structural information for link prediction. We show that incorporating distance information into the decoder leads to more expressive models and improved predictive performance.

