\section{Ablation Study}

To understand the contribution of different components of our model, we perform an ablation study by gradually adding distance information and analyzing its impact on link prediction performance.

\vspace{0.5em}

\subsection{Effect of Distance Information}

We first evaluate how shortest-path distance affects link prediction. We compare three settings: (1) a baseline MLP decoder without distance information, (2) a decoder that concatenates raw shortest-path distance, and (3) a decoder that uses distance embeddings.

\vspace{0.5em}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Effect of Distance Information on Link Prediction Performance}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|}
\hline
\textbf{Model Variant} & \textbf{AUC} \\
\hline
MLP Decoder (No Distance) & 0.77 \\
\hline
Distance Concatenation (Raw Distance) & 0.85 \\
\hline
Distance Embedding & 0.86 \\
\hline
Distance-Conditioned AdaLN & 0.88 \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\label{tab:ablation}
\end{center}
\end{table}

\vspace{0.5em}

\vspace{0.5em}

The results show that incorporating shortest-path distance significantly improves performance compared to using node embeddings alone. Furthermore, representing distance using embeddings performs slightly better than using raw distance values, indicating that high-dimensional distance representations are more expressive.

\vspace{0.5em}

\subsection{Effect of Distance Modulation}

We next evaluate the impact of distance-conditioned modulation. Instead of directly concatenating distance embeddings with node embeddings, the AdaLN decoder uses distance embeddings to modulate node representations through learned shift and scale parameters.

\vspace{0.5em}

The results show that distance-conditioned modulation performs better than simple concatenation. This suggests that allowing distance to influence node representations before link prediction is more effective than treating distance as an additional feature.

\vspace{0.5em}

\subsection{Effect of Maximum Distance}

Since very large shortest-path distances may not provide useful information for link prediction, we clip distances to a maximum value $D_{max}$. We evaluate the effect of different values of $D_{max}$.

